{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2018}}
'''Lazarus Geiger''' (21 May 1829 – 29 August 1870) was a German Jewish philosopher and [[philologist]].

==Life==
He was born at [[Frankfurt-on-Main]], was destined to commerce, but soon gave himself up to scholarship and studied at [[University of Marburg|Marburg]], [[University of Bonn|Bonn]] and [[University of Heidelberg|Heidelberg]]. From 1861 till his sudden death in 1870 he was professor in the Jewish high school at Frankfurt. His chief aim was to prove that the evolution of human reason is closely bound up with that of language. He further maintained that the origin of the [[Indo-Germanic]] language is to be sought not in Asia but in central (Germany). He was a convinced opponent of [[rationalism]] in religion.{{sfn|Chisholm|1911|p=551}}

{{quote|It was Lazarus Geiger, ... who first detected universal sequence in the acquisition of basic colour terms.{{sfn|Berlin|Kay|1991|p=135 }}}}

==Bibliography==
Lazarus Geiger's chief work was ''Ursprung und Entwickelung der menschlichen Sprache und Vernunft'' (vol. i., Stuttgart, 1868), the principal results of which appeared in a more popular form as ''Der Ursprung der Sprache'' (Stuttgart, 1869 and 1878). The second volume of the former was published in an incomplete form (1872, 2nd ed. 1899) after his death by his brother Alfred Geiger.{{sfn|Chisholm|1911|p=551}}

Alfred Geiger also published a number of Lazarus Geiger's scattered papers as ''Zur Entwickelung der Menschheit'' (1871, and ed. 1878; Eng. trans. D. Asher, ''Hist. of the Development of the Human Race'', London, 1880).{{sfn|Chisholm|1911|p=551}}

